response.stringValue: Exercise-induced asthma is actually called exercise-induced bronchoconstriction (EIB for short)

title.stringValue: It's an obstruction to the airway that happens because of exercise

response.stringValue: Symptoms don't usually happen right at the start of exercise. They can begin during exercise, and are usually worse 5-10 minutes after
Symptoms usually resolve 20-30 minutes after stopping exercise - although some people will experience a second wave of symptoms 4-12 hours laters

title.stringValue: Not everyone experiences all of these symptoms during exercise by the way! Coughing, which is the most common symptom, may be your only symptom

response.stringValue: When you exercise, your body demands more oxygen, and you end up breathing faster and deeper than normal
During exercise, you typically breathe through your mouth (not your nose), causing the air reaching your lungs to be dryer and colder
